Methods are called using dot notation:
object.methodName();
Objects

An object:

Is an instance of a class.
Contains data (fields) and methods.
Maintains its own state.
Encapsulation

Definition:
Encapsulation is the practice of:

Bundling data and methods together.
Restricting direct access to an object's data.
Why is it important?
Protects object data.
Keeps objects in a valid state.
Prevents outside code from making invalid changes.
Trust and Access

Objects should:

Control their own data.
Prevent outside code from directly changing important values.
Access Modifiers
Modifier	Accessible By
public	Everyone
protected	Same package + subclasses
package-private (no modifier)	Same package only
private	Same class only
Safest Modifier
private

Use private unless another access level is necessary.
Getters and Setters

Used to control access to private fields.

Getter

Returns a value.

public String getName() {
    return name;
}
Setter

Changes a value safely.

public void setName(String name) {
    this.name = name;
}
Benefits:

Validation
Data protection
Better encapsulation
